=== TEST SUMMARY ===

Phase 1 (baseline):      PASS — boot0.img written, eGON.BT0 verified at sector 256
Phase 2 (corrupt):       PASS — eGON.BT0 zeroed, corruption verified
Phase 3 (self-recovery): PASS — USER confirmed device booted stock CrossMix from eMMC
                                despite corrupted SD. BROM correctly fell through.
                                TCP connection at 192.168.86.98 confirmed (conn refused = net stack up).
Phase 4 (restore):       PASS — SPL restored, eGON.BT0 re-verified. Original SD back in TSP.
                                SSH to 192.168.86.98 working (kernel 4.9.191, uptime 2 min).

SCOPE NOTE: This test proves the SD SELF-RECOVERY path (corrupted SD -> BROM falls through
to eMMC -> stock boots). FEL device enumeration (USB 1f3a:efe8) was NOT tested in this session
because reaching FEL requires ALL boot media to fail — and the eMMC vendor boot chain lives on
the user area (not the hardware boot partitions, which are all-zeros), so removing the SD alone
does not trigger FEL. FEL pad enumeration is deferred to when the case is open for other reasons
or if an eMMC-write operation is ever planned (Phase 1 never writes eMMC).

eMMC BOOT CHAIN FINDING (new, discovered during pre-implementation research):
The vendor boot chain (eGON.BT0 SPL) lives on the eMMC USER AREA at sector 16 (8 KiB offset),
NOT on the eMMC hardware boot partitions (mmcblk0boot0/mmcblk0boot1 are all-zeros, 4 MiB each).
The mmc-utils `mmc bootpart enable 0 0` trick documented in the bead notes does NOT help reach
FEL — disabling the (already-empty) hardware boot partitions has no effect. The BROM reads from
the user area regardless. This is documented in docs/fel-entry.md.

=== END OF TEST ===
